<%= faq_schema([
  { question: "How is alimony calculated?", answer: "Alimony formulas vary widely by US state. The most common approach (the 'AAML formula' from the American Academy of Matrimonial Lawyers) takes 30% of the higher-earning spouse's income, subtracts 20% of the lower-earning spouse's income, and caps the result so the total payments don't push the recipient above 40% of combined income. Other states use percentage-of-marriage-length formulas, judicial discretion, or income-shares models. This calculator uses the AAML formula as a national approximation; your actual state may differ significantly." },
  { question: "How long does alimony last?", answer: "Duration depends on marriage length. For marriages under 5 years, alimony typically lasts 0–25% of the marriage length (so a 4-year marriage might get 1 year of alimony). For marriages 5–10 years, 30–50% of the marriage length. For marriages 10–20 years, 50–70%. For marriages over 20 years, alimony can be indefinite or last 80%+ of the marriage length. These are approximations — every state has its own statutory or judicial guidelines, and individual circumstances heavily influence outcomes." },
  { question: "Do men ever get alimony?", answer: "Yes — about 3% of US alimony payments go to men (US Census Bureau, 2010s data). The law is gender-neutral; courts award alimony based on income disparity, not gender. The reason men receive alimony less often is mostly historical income gap — in marriages where the wife is the higher earner, courts award alimony to the husband. The number is rising as more women out-earn their husbands, and is expected to continue climbing." },
  { question: "Can alimony be modified?", answer: "Yes, in most states. Modifications usually require a 'substantial change in circumstances' — job loss, disability, retirement, or remarriage of the recipient. Some states automatically end alimony when the recipient remarries; others require a motion. Voluntary income reductions (quitting a job to lower payments) generally don't qualify as a change in circumstance and can result in contempt charges. Both spouses can petition for modification; it requires going back to court." },
  { question: "Is alimony taxable?", answer: "For divorces finalized after January 1, 2019, no — under the 2017 Tax Cuts and Jobs Act, alimony is no longer tax-deductible for the payor or taxable to the recipient. For divorces finalized before 2019, the old rules still apply (deductible/taxable). This change shifted billions in tax liability and dramatically reduced incentives to negotiate larger alimony amounts. State tax treatment varies and may differ from federal." }
]) %>

