    <article class="prose dark:prose-invert max-w-none">
      <h2>How the Alimony Calculator Works</h2>
      <p>
        The calculator uses the most widely-cited national alimony formula, sometimes called the AAML formula (American Academy of Matrimonial Lawyers): 30% of the payor's gross income minus 20% of the recipient's gross income, capped so the total doesn't push the recipient above 40% of combined income. Duration is estimated based on marriage length using a graduated scale: shorter marriages get shorter alimony as a percentage, longer marriages get longer durations. This is a simplified national approximation — your actual state may use a completely different formula or leave it entirely up to judicial discretion.
      </p>

      <div class="my-6"><%= render "shared/ad_slot", slot: "in_content" %></div>

      <h2>State-by-State Variation Is Massive</h2>
      <p>
        Alimony is one of the least standardized areas of US family law. Texas has very limited alimony, capped at $5,000/month and 10 years maximum, and only available after 10+ year marriages. Massachusetts uses a strict formula with set durations. Florida has guidelines but heavy judicial discretion. California uses a complex formula plus 10+ statutory factors. New York has formulas but allows huge deviations. Some states (Mississippi, North Carolina) have no formula at all and leave everything to judges. This calculator is a starting point — for actual planning, consult a family law attorney in your state.
      </p>

      <h2>Types of Alimony</h2>
      <p>
        Most states recognize several types: <strong>temporary</strong> (during the divorce proceedings), <strong>rehabilitative</strong> (helps the recipient become self-supporting through education or training, usually 2–5 years), <strong>permanent</strong> (until death or remarriage of recipient, mostly for long marriages or older spouses), <strong>reimbursement</strong> (compensates for sacrifices made during the marriage, like supporting a spouse through medical school), and <strong>lump sum</strong> (a one-time payment instead of monthly). The calculator estimates monthly amounts under the most common type — durational or rehabilitative — but doesn't distinguish between forms.
      </p>

      <h2>Factors Courts Consider Beyond the Formula</h2>
      <p>
        Even in formula states, judges weigh many factors: standard of living during the marriage, age and health of both spouses, ability to earn, contributions to the marriage (including stay-at-home parenting), tax consequences, child custody arrangements, and any prenuptial agreements. A spouse who gave up a career to raise children may receive longer alimony than the formula suggests. A spouse who has significant separate property may receive less. None of this shows up in a simple calculator — but it's the human element that often dominates real cases.
      </p>

      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

      <h3>Is alimony guaranteed in a divorce?</h3>
      <p>No — alimony is awarded only if there's significant income disparity and the marriage was long enough.</p>

      <h3>What if both spouses earn the same?</h3>
      <p>Then alimony is usually $0. Some states require minimum income gaps to even consider alimony.</p>

      <h3>Can alimony be waived in a prenup?</h3>
      <p>Yes, in most states. Properly drafted prenups can waive alimony entirely.</p>

      <h3>Does cohabitation end alimony?</h3>
      <p>In many states, yes — the recipient living with a new partner can reduce or end payments.</p>

      <h3>Should I hire an attorney for an alimony dispute?</h3>
      <p>Yes — alimony has long-term financial implications. Don't negotiate it alone.</p>

